{"title_page": "Ahenema", "text_new": "'''Ahenema''' is a royal traditional slipper worn by chiefs and queens of the [[Akan people|Akan]], [[Ga-Adangbe people|Ga]], and [[Ewe people|Ewe]] ethnic groups in [[Ghana]]. In recent times this traditional slipper can be worn by anyone to events such as festivals, funerals, marriage ceremonies and to church.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The worth of \"Ahenema\" in today\u2019s fashion|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/The-worth-of-Ahenema-in-today-s-fashion-355545|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Hidden Treasures of Ghana....Exhibit the Royalty of Ahenema|url=http://businessdayghana.com/hidden-treasures-of-ghana-exhibit-the-royalty-of-ahenema/|last=Desk|first=Business|date=2016-04-25|website=Business Day Ghana|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-06}}</ref>[[File:Ahenema slippers.jpg|thumb|Ahenema slippers]]\n\n== History ==\nIn the past, Ahenema was strictly worn by people of royal descent and was often named after the king. This method of naming was later changed, to be named after the children of the king. This was because the kings' name should not be mentioned in vain hence Ahenema which translates as king's children. The slipper was formally made of wood and rope however it is now made with leather. The sole of an Ahenema slipper is carved into the number 8 which represents stability.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Asubonteng|first=K|last2=Boahin|first2=J.O.B|last3=Azuah|first3=Scholastica|date=2016|title=Transposing Ahenema Footwear in Contemporary Ghanaian Youth Fashion|url=http://www.ijarset.com/upload/2016/may/32_IJARSET_john_2.pdf|journal=International Journal of Advanced Research in Science, Engineering and Technology|volume=3|pages=|via=IJARSET}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Ahenema Ghanian Slippers|url=https://www.adolophine.com/shop/ahenema-ghanian-slippers|website=ADOLOPHINE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-06}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\nThere are basically two types of Ahenema. One being \"Asansan tuo\" which is designed to have a curved shape and the other \"Atine\" which has a straight shape and worn mostly by chiefs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Asubonteng|first=K|last2=Boahin|first2=J.O.B|last3=Azuah|first3=Scholastica|date=2016|title=Transposing Ahenema Footwear in Contemporary Ghanaian Youth Fashion|url=http://www.ijarset.com/upload/2016/may/32_IJARSET_john_2.pdf|journal=International Journal of Advanced Research in Science, Engineering and Technology|volume=3|pages=|via=IJARSET}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Akan culture]]\n[[Category:African clothing]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''Ahenema''' is a royal traditional slipper worn by chiefs and queens of the [[Akan people|Akan]], [[Ga-Adangbe people|Ga]], and [[Ewe people|Ewe]] ethnic groups in [[Ghana]]. In recent times this traditional slipper can be worn by anyone to events such as festivals, funerals, marriage ceremonies and to church.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The worth of \u201cAhenema\u201d in today\u2019s fashion|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/The-worth-of-Ahenema-in-today-s-fashion-355545|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Hidden Treasures of Ghana....Exhibit the Royalty of Ahenema|url=http://businessdayghana.com/hidden-treasures-of-ghana-exhibit-the-royalty-of-ahenema/|last=Desk|first=Business|date=2016-04-25|website=Business Day Ghana|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-06}}</ref>[[File:Ahenema slippers.jpg|thumb|Ahenema slippers]]\n\n== History ==\nIn the past, Ahenema was strictly worn by people of royal descent and was often named after the king. This method of naming was later changed, to be named after the children of the king. This was because the kings' name should not be mentioned in vain hence Ahenema which translates as king's children. The slipper was formally made of wood and rope however it is now made with leather. The sole of an Ahenema slipper is carved into the number 8 which represents stability.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Asubonteng|first=K|last2=Boahin|first2=J.O.B|last3=Azuah|first3=Scholastica|date=2016|title=Transposing Ahenema Footwear in Contemporary Ghanaian Youth Fashion|url=http://www.ijarset.com/upload/2016/may/32_IJARSET_john_2.pdf|journal=International Journal of Advanced Research in Science, Engineering and Technology|volume=3|pages=|via=IJARSET}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|title=Ahenema Ghanian Slippers|url=https://www.adolophine.com/shop/ahenema-ghanian-slippers|website=ADOLOPHINE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-06}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\nThere are basically two types of Ahenema. One being \"Asansan tuo\" which is designed to have a curved shape and the other \"Atine\" which has a straight shape and worn mostly by chiefs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Asubonteng|first=K|last2=Boahin|first2=J.O.B|last3=Azuah|first3=Scholastica|date=2016|title=Transposing Ahenema Footwear in Contemporary Ghanaian Youth Fashion|url=http://www.ijarset.com/upload/2016/may/32_IJARSET_john_2.pdf|journal=International Journal of Advanced Research in Science, Engineering and Technology|volume=3|pages=|via=IJARSET}}</ref>\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{Ghana-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Akan culture]]\n[[Category:African clothing]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ahenema"}
